                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d337">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">662.116 Lard/23: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dodd</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-06-05T16:00:00+01:00"
                            >June 5, 1934—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 5—1 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>105. For the Department of Agriculture.</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“For Wheeler, Foreign Service Agriculture. Reference our cable, May 18th,
                        also Embassy’s cable May 22nd. Import quotas assigned importers American
                        lard for June only 17 percent basic average. Also reported Germany purchased
                        3,000 metric tons Hungarian lard at 45 pfennigs pound. <hi rend="italic"
                            >Fettstelle</hi> does not deny this but says purchase represents year’s
                        quota. This amount presumably established by German-Hungarian treaty April
                        1, 1934, and is four times the total lard imports from Hungary during past 4
                        years. Christy.”</p>
                </quote>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dodd</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
